Setting up RSelenium

Elgar Teo

4/12/2020

RSelenium is an R package that allows the use of Selenium Server, a program for crawling data from web pages through browser automation, in R.

Prerequisites

We’ll be using the Command Prompt (for Windows)/Terminal (for Mac) in the process. You can skip this part if you already know how to use it to navigate through folders in your computer.

Windows

The quickest way to launch Command Prompt is to press the key combination + R ( is the key between Ctrl and Alt). A Run dialog will show up. Type cmd and click OK. The Command Prompt will then be open:

By default, the working directory of Command Prompt is your home folder, which is C:\Users\YOUR_USRE_NAME\. All your personal files fall under this folder most of the time. For example, your Documents folder is a sub-folder of this home folder (C:\Users\YOUR_USRE_NAME\Documents). Same for the Downloads folder (C:\Users\YOUR_USRE_NAME\Downloads) and Desktop (C:\Users\YOUR_USRE_NAME\Desktop).

You can use the command cd FOLDER_NAME to change the working directory, with a backslash \ separating each folder. For example, if your want to access a folder jmsc6116 on your desktop, you can use the command cd Desktop\jmsc6116 to do so. If you want to go back to the folder one level up, type cd ...

Mac

Click on the search icon on the menu bar on the top right hand corner of your screen. Type terminal and launch Terminal.

By default, the working directory of Terminal is your home folder, which is /Users/YOUR_USER_NAME. All your personal files fall under this folder most of the time. For example, your Documents folder is a sub-folder of this home folder (/Users/YOUR_USER_NAME/Documents). Same for the Downloads folder (/Users/YOUR_USER_NAME/Downloads) and Desktop (/Users/YOUR_USER_NAME/Desktop).

You can use the command cd FOLDER_NAME to change the working directory, with a slash / separating each folder. For example, if your want to access a folder jmsc6116 on your desktop, you can use the command cd Desktop/jmsc6116 to do so. If you want to go back to the folder one level up, type cd ...

Installing

You need these five things on your machine for RSelenium to run:

  1. Chrome browser
  2. Java Development Kit (JDK)
  3. Selenium Server
  4. Browser Driver
  5. RSelenium

I assume all of you already have Chrome installed on your computer.

JDK

RSelenium requires JDK to run. You can check whether you already have it by typing javac -version in the Command Prompt/Terminal. If you see javac 16, you can skip this part. This tutorial is based on JDK version 16. Other versions may work, but if you run into errors please intall JDK 16.

Download JDK here. For Windows, download jdk-16.0.1_windows-x64_bin.exe. For Mac, download jdk-16.0.1_osx-x64_bin.dmg. Then proceed with the installation.

To check whether JDK is properly installed, type javac -version in the Command Prompt/Terminal. You should see javac 16.

Selenium Server

Download Selenium Server here. Save it in a folder of your choice and remember the folder path, to which we refer as SELENIUM_FOLDER below.

Browser Driver

The browser driver acts as a “middleman” between Selenium Server and the browser so that Selenium Server can control the browser. We’re using Chrome in this tutorial, but Selenium Server also supports a wide variety of browsers so if you’re interested in using other browsers you can look for the respective drivers.

First, check which version of Chrome you have:

Then, go here and look for the folder with the name corresponding to your Chrome’s version number. For example, if your Chrome version is 90.0.4430.24, go to the folder 90.0.4430.24. If you can’t find your version, choose the folder with the closest previous version, e.g. go to 90.0.4430.24 if you have 90.0.4430.85. In the folder, download chromedriver_win32.zip for Windows, chromedriver_mac64.zip for Intel Mac or chromedriver_mac64_m1.zip for M1 Mac.

After downloading, unzip the file and save its content chromedriver in the same folder where you placed the Selenium Server file, i.e. SELENIUM_FOLDER.

RSelenium

Open RStudio and install the package RSelenium:

install.packages("RSelenium")

Using RSelenium

To use RSelenium, you need to have Selenium Server up and running first.

Open Command Prompt/Terminal and switch to the folder where you saved the Selenium Server file and the browser driver:

cd SELENIUM_FOLDER

Then launch Selenium Server with the following command in Mac:

java -Dwebdriver.chrome.driver=chromedriver -jar selenium-server-standalone-3.141.59.jar -port 4444

in Windows:

java -Dwebdriver.chrome.driver=chromedriver.exe -jar selenium-server-standalone-3.141.59.jar -port 4444

If everything is working fine, your should see a bunch of text showing up with the last line being Selenium Server is up and running on port 4444 (the screenshot below shows 4445 but yours should say 4444):

DO NOT close the Command Prompt/Terminal window while using RSelenium!

Open RStudio and run the following test commands:

require(RSelenium)
rD <- remoteDriver(remoteServerAddr = "localhost", port = 4444L, browserName = "chrome")
rD$open()
rD$navigate("http://www.bbc.com")

If you’re running RSelenium for the first time on a Mac, you may encounter error. Please refer to the section below.

You should see a chrome browser window showing up and loading BBC’s website automatically:

Special Note for Mac Users

You may encounter error with this dialog showing up when running RSelenium for the first time:

DO NOT click on Move to Bin! Cancel it instead.

Open up System Preferences and go to Secutiry & Privacy:

Click on Allow Anyway.

Go back to RStudio and run the test commands again. You’ll see this dialog popping up this time:

DO NOT click on Move to Bin! Click Open.

It should be working now. And no worries, this problem only shows up when you’re running RSelenium for the first time.

Closing RSelenium

To close RSelenium properly, run the following command:

rD$close

Afterwards, switch to the Command Prompt/Terminal window where Selenium Server is running and press the key combination Ctrl + C (same for both Windows and Mac). This will terminate Selenium Server. You can then close the Command Prompt/Terminal window.
